  "problemSolved": {
    "statement": "Reductionism encompasses a set of ontological, epistemological, and methodological claims about the relations between different scientific domains. The basic question of reduction is whether the properties, concepts, explanations, or methods from one scientific domain (typically at higher levels of organization) can be deduced from or explained by the properties, concepts, explanations, or methods from another domain of science (typically at lower levels of organization). Reduction is germane to a variety of issues in philosophy of science, including the structure of scientific theories, the relations between scientific disciplines, the nature of explanation, the diversity of methodology, and notions of theoretical progress, as well as to numerous topics in metaphysics and philosophy of mind, such as emergence, mereology, and supervenience. Questions about reduction in biology are pervasive throughout the history of philosophy and science. Many contemporary debates have historical analogues that reflect long-standing controversies about the legitimacy of reductionist research strategies and modes of explanation used by different life science subdisciplines. In philosophy of biology, debates about reduction in the second half of the 20th century focused traditionally on the question of whether and in what sense classical genetics can be reduced to molecular biology (although other strands of discussion were present, such as whether evolutionary theory is inherently anti-reductionist because of the principle of natural selection). Philosophical debates now address a wider array of domains beyond genetics (e.g., development, ecology, evolution, cell biology, and neuroscience), and include additional questions about the nature and status of interdisciplinarity, such as the integration of data or standards across biological fields. Section 1 gives an overview of the idea of reduction and how it connects to biological domains and other philosophical issues. Since debates about reductionism have been going on long before recent discussions in philosophy of biology, Section 2 offers some historical background. Section 3 reviews the main philosophical accounts of reduction in light of their respective motivations and limitations. More general objections to the feasibility or scientific relevance of reduction are discussed in Section 4. Because most philosophical discussions during the past two decades have largely focused on other models of the structure of scientific knowledge than reduction (e.g., integration), Sections 5 and 6 concentrate on these recent issues and trends.",
